{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_018xTfcYAkTPmstFZrZJg61U","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Fp5FmeQAAsBmMNdASexfyp","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The traveling-salesman heuristic produces a route that is no more than 1.5x the length of the optimal route for inputs up to 20 stops.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior tests a pure algorithmic function with no I/O or external dependencies. The failure boundary is entirely within the TSP algorithm itself. We can generate test coordinates (10-20 points), call the heuristic, compute or reference the optimal route length, and verify the constraint. No mocking or infrastructure is needed—this is pure computation.","test_description":"Create deterministic test datasets of coordinates (various sizes 5-20 stops, different geometric patterns), run the TSP heuristic on each, compute the optimal or known-good route length via brute force for small sets, and assert that the heuristic output is ≤1.5x optimal for all test cases.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"A Unit test directly verifies the algorithm's output against the constraint. No lower level exists; no higher level is needed.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.94,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The delivery time window estimates are computed correctly from the distance between consecutive stops and the configured average speed for the road type.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior tests a deterministic calculation: time = distance / speed, applied to each segment between consecutive stops. The failure boundary is in the calculation logic itself. We can provide test stops/distances and speed configuration directly (either computed or mocked), call the time-window function, and verify the math. The function logic does not depend on real geocoding or routing output—we can provide these inputs directly in a Unit test.","test_description":"Create test stops with known distances between them, configure speed values for road types, call compute_delivery_windows() with these inputs, and assert that each segment's time equals distance divided by the configured speed, and that cumulative times are correct.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test directly provides inputs and verifies the calculation. The core failure (wrong formula, wrong speed lookup, off-by-one error) is caught at Unit level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The shift-hours validator rejects a route whose total estimated time exceeds the driver's remaining shift hours, returning the excess amount.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a simple validation function with pure logic: compare total_time against remaining_shift, return rejection flag and excess. No I/O, no external dependencies, no infrastructure needed. We provide simple numeric inputs and verify the logic directly. Any bug (off-by-one, comparison direction, wrong excess calculation) is caught immediately.","test_description":"Create test cases with total_time both exceeding and within remaining_shift (boundary cases: exact fit, 1 minute over, large excess), call the validator for each, assert rejection status is correct and excess amount is accurate (or zero if within limits).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test provides inputs and verifies output. No dependencies or integration needed; the function logic is the failure boundary.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.96,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When one address in the list fails geocoding (API returns no results), the service skips that stop and optimizes the remaining addresses, reporting which addresses were skipped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior involves integration between address-list processing, geocoding API error handling, filtering logic, and route optimization. While we could mock the geocoding API at Unit level to return 'no results,' the real failure risk lies in integration: the service must correctly parse the actual API's error response format (which could vary: empty list, None, error object, exception), wire the error through the filtering logic, and ensure the remaining stops are routed correctly. A Unit test with a simple mocked response might pass but the real code could fail if the API returns a different error format or raises an exception. Integration level with a realistic mock or a controlled real API is the minimum to catch this class of failures.","test_description":"Mock the geocoding service to return 'no results' (empty/None) for one address in a test list and valid coordinates for others, call optimize_route() with this mixed input, assert that the skipped address is reported in output.skipped, verify the returned route visits only the non-failed addresses, and confirm the route optimization runs correctly on the remaining stops.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test exercises the integration path from API error response through filtering to route optimization. A Unit test mocking only the response would be less robust to real API behavior variance.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate addresses in the input list are consolidated into a single stop with combined delivery items, not visited twice.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior tests pure deduplication and aggregation logic within the service. No external dependencies, no I/O. The failure boundary is in the service's address-consolidation logic. We provide a test input with duplicate addresses (and associated delivery items) and verify that the output contains exactly one stop for each unique address with merged items, and that the route visits each unique address only once. A Unit test directly catches any bug in the deduplication or merging logic.","test_description":"Create a test input with duplicate addresses (same address repeated 2-3 times) each with different delivery items, call the address-consolidation step, assert each unique address appears only once in the consolidated list, verify delivery items for duplicates are combined (e.g., item counts summed or lists merged), and confirm the final route visits each unique stop exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test provides inputs and directly verifies deduplication and consolidation. No integration or external calls needed.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.92,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13783,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13783},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e4d86fd9-2c72-4536-8318-74da7a320c1a","uuid":"ae6f4cbd-1c83-4ed9-ab50-9b98ec64379a"}
